Accessibility Review Document
Website Reviewed: https://www.testleaf.com/
Standard Referenced: WCAG 2.x Guidelines

🔎 Summary of Findings
The following accessibility issues were identified during the review. Each issue includes the affected element, an example fix, WCAG reference, and risk level.

1️⃣ Missing lang Attribute
Affected Tag: <html>
Recommended Implementation:
<html lang="en">


WCAG Guideline: 3.1.1 – Language of Page
Risk Level: 🔴 High
Impact: Screen readers may not correctly interpret and announce the page language, leading to mispronunciation and confusion for users relying on assistive technologies.

2️⃣ Insufficient Color Contrast
Affected Selector: .header
Current Example:
.header {
    background-color: #333;
    color: #fff;
}


WCAG Guideline: 1.4.3 – Contrast (Minimum)
Risk Level: 🟠 Medium
Impact: Users with low vision or color vision deficiencies may struggle to read text content if contrast ratios do not meet the minimum 4.5:1 requirement.

3️⃣ Missing Alternative Text for Images
Affected Tag: <img>
Incorrect Example:
<img src="logo.png">


Correct Implementation:
<img src="logo.png" alt="TestLeaf Logo">


WCAG Guideline: 1.1.1 – Non-text Content
Risk Level: 🔴 High
Impact: Screen readers cannot describe images to visually impaired users without meaningful alt text.

4️⃣ Inaccessible Navigation Structure
Affected Tag: <nav>
Recommended Implementation:
<nav role="navigation">
    ...
</nav>


WCAG Guideline: 2.4.1 – Bypass Blocks / Navigation
Risk Level: 🟠 Medium
Impact: Improperly structured navigation can make it difficult for assistive technology users to move efficiently through the page.

5️⃣ Missing ARIA Labels on Input Fields
Affected Tag: <input type="search">
Recommended Implementation:
<input type="search" aria-label="Search">


WCAG Guideline: 2.5.3 – Label in Name
Risk Level: 🟠 Medium
Impact: Without accessible labels, screen readers may not correctly describe the purpose of form inputs.

6️⃣ Inconsistent Heading Structure
Affected Tags: <h1>, <h2>, <h3>
Recommendation:
Maintain a logical and hierarchical heading structure (e.g., one <h1> per page, followed by properly nested <h2>, <h3>, etc.).
WCAG Guideline: 1.3.1 – Info and Relationships
Risk Level: 🟠 Medium
Impact: Improper heading order can make it difficult for users to understand content structure and navigate efficiently using assistive tools.

7️⃣ Missing Closed Captions for Audio/Video
Affected Tags: <video>, <audio>
Recommendation:
Provide synchronized captions and transcripts for multimedia content.
WCAG Guideline: 1.2.2 – Captions (Prerecorded)
Risk Level: 🔴 High
Impact: Users with hearing impairments may not be able to access essential information presented in audio or video format.

8️⃣ Inaccessible Form Elements
Affected Tags: <form>, <input>, <select>
Recommended Implementation Example:
<label for="email">Email</label>
<input type="email" id="email" name="email">


WCAG Guideline: 2.1.2 – No Keyboard Trap
Risk Level: 🟠 Medium
Impact: Forms without proper labels and keyboard accessibility can prevent users with disabilities from completing tasks.

📌 Overall Recommendations
✔ Add missing lang attribute to the root HTML element
✔ Ensure all images contain meaningful alternative text
✔ Verify color contrast ratios meet WCAG minimum requirements
✔ Maintain semantic HTML structure with proper heading hierarchy
✔ Provide ARIA attributes where necessary (without overusing them)
✔ Ensure full keyboard accessibility across navigation and forms
✔ Add captions and transcripts to multimedia content
✔ Conduct manual testing using screen readers (NVDA/VoiceOver) and keyboard-only navigation


